{{Infobox award | name = Philip Merrill Award for Outstanding Contributions to Liberal Arts Education | description = Advancement of [[liberal arts education]] | presenter = [[American Council of Trustees and Alumni]] | location = [[Washington, District of Columbia]] | year = 2005 | website = {{url|www.goacta.org}} }} The '''Philip Merrill Award for Outstanding Contributions to Liberal Arts Education''' is an annual prize given by the [[American Council of Trustees and Alumni]] to an individual who has “made an extraordinary contribution to the advancement of liberal arts education, core curricula, and the teaching of [[Western civilization]] and [[American history]].” The award is named for the late public servant, publisher, entrepreneur, and philanthropist [[Philip Merrill]].
Merrill was a trustee of [[Cornell University]], the [[University of Maryland]] Foundation, the [[Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies]], the [[Smithsonian National Museum of American History]], and the [[Aspen Institute]], as well as a member of the National Council of the American Council of Trustees and Alumni.
==Winners== * 2005: [[Robert P. George]], McCormick Professor of Jurisprudence, [[Princeton University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lapa.princeton.edu/peopledetail.php?ID=306|title=Faculty Associate Robert P. George|publisher=[[Princeton University]]|accessdate=March 12, 2012}}</ref> * 2006: [[Harvey C. Mansfield]], William R. Kenan, Jr. Professor of Government, [[Harvard University]] * 2007: [[Gertrude Himmelfarb]], Professor Emerita, [[City University of New York]] * 2008: [[Donald Kagan]], Sterling Professor of History and Classics, [[Yale University]] * 2009: [[KC Johnson]], Professor of History, [[Brooklyn College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/pub/Faculty_Details5.jsp?faculty=25|title=KC Johnson |publisher=[[Brooklyn College, City University of New York|Brookyln College]]|accessdate=March 12, 2012}}</ref> * 2010: [[Benno C. Schmidt, Jr.|Benno Schmidt]], Chairman of the Board of Trustees, [[City University of New York]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cuny.edu/mu/forum/2010/08/02/statement-from-chancellor-matthew-goldstein-on-the-philip-merrill-award-to-cuny-chairman-benno-schmidt/|title=Statement from Chancellor Matthew Goldstein on the Philip Merrill Award to CUNY Chairman Benno Schmidt |publisher=[[City University of New York]]|date=August 2, 2010|accessdate=March 12, 2012}}</ref> * 2011: [[David McCullough]], independent scholar<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/blogarticles/21528.html|title=American Council of Trustees and Alumni Philip Merrill Award |publisher=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|''Washingtonian'']]|date=November 10, 2011|accessdate=February 13, 2012}}</ref> * 2012: Tom Rollins, founder of the [[Teaching Company]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Rollins to Receive 2012 Philip Merrill Prize|url=http://www.goacta.org/whatsNew/tom_rollins_to_receive_2012_philip_merrill_prize|accessdate=10 January 2013|newspaper=American Council of Trustees and Alumni|date=2012-10-21}}</ref> * 2013: Gary Gallagher, Professor of History, [[University of Virginia]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Gallagher wins 2013 Merrill Award|url=http://history.virginia.edu/node/2773|accessdate=28 September 2013|newspaper=Corcoran Department of History}}</ref> * 2014: [[Louise Mirrer]], president and CEO of the [[New-York Historical Society]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Philip Merrill Award|url=http://www.goacta.org/initiatives/annual_conference|publisher=American Council of Trustees and Alumni|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> * 2015: [[Hank Brown]], former [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] [[politician]] and [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Colorado]] who served as president of the [[University of Colorado system]] from April 2005 to January 2008. * 2016: [[Niall Ferguson]] and [[Ayaan Hirsi Ali]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Ayaan Hirsi Ali and Niall Ferguson to Receive Award at Annual Higher Education Conference|url=https://www.goacta.org/news/ayaan_hirsi_ali_and_niall_ferguson_to_receive_award_at_annual_higher_educat|accessdate=2 December 2016|publisher=American Council of Trustees and Alumni|date=October 19, 2016}}</ref> * 2017: [[Robert Zimmer]], President, [[University of Chicago]] <ref>{{cite news|title=ACTA Announces Robert Zimmer as 2017 Philip Merrill Award Receipient|url=https://www.goacta.org/whatsNew/acta-announces-robert-zimmer-as-2017-philip-merrill-award-recipient|accessdate=14 August 2018|publisher=American Council of Trustees and Alumni|date=May 11, 2017}}</ref> * 2018: [[Mitch Daniels]], President, [[Purdue University]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Purdue University President to Receive ACTA’s National Award for Commitment to Academic Freedom and Affordability|url=https://www.goacta.org/news/purdue-university-president-to-receive-actas-national-award-for-commitment-to-academic-freedom-and-affordability|accessdate=14 August 2018|publisher=American Council of Trustees and Alumni|date=April 25, 2018}}</ref>
