{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}} {{Use British English|date=March 2018}} {{infobox University |image_name= |image_size= 200px |name= WMG |established= 1980 |city= [[Coventry]] |country= [[United Kingdom]] |website=[http://www.wmg.warwick.ac.uk/ www.wmg.warwick.ac.uk] |director=[[Kumar Bhattacharyya, Baron Bhattacharyya|Professor Lord (Kumar) Bhattacharyya]] |location=[[Coventry]], [[United Kingdom]] |campus=Semi-rural ([[University of Warwick]]) |address= WMG, [[University of Warwick]], Coventry, CV4 7AL, United Kingdom }}
The '''Warwick Manufacturing Group''' (today known as '''WMG''') is an academic department at the [[University of Warwick]], providing research, education and knowledge transfer in engineering, manufacturing and technology. The group provides taught and research degrees for [[postgraduate]] students at the University of Warwick campus in England, and at overseas centres in [[China]], [[India]], [[Singapore]], [[Malaysia]], [[Cyprus]], [[Russia]] and [[Thailand]].
==History== The Warwick Manufacturing Group was founded in 1980 by [[Kumar Bhattacharyya, Baron Bhattacharyya|Kumar Bhattacharyya]] to support the reinvigoration of UK manufacturing through research and knowledge transfer (Bhattacharyya, made a [[life peer]] in 2004, remains chairman of WMG). Its first venture was a part-time master's degree for senior industry staff; this considered technology and management as a unified whole, with modules taught at a purpose-built residential centre.<ref name=THEJump>{{cite news|last=Jump|first=Paul|title=Where research shares the driver's seat with industry|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/414726.article|accessdate=10 December 2013|newspaper=Times Higher Education|date=6 January 2011}}</ref> While the course was initially criticised by academics, it proved popular with industry and companies began to send staff to WMG in greater numbers.
Bhattacharyya then decided to provide industry-related research services too,<ref name=THEJump /> convincing the university to loan money for a centre where academics could collaborate with industrialists on the development of new products for the aerospace and automotive industries. The advanced technology centre was officially opened on 8 January 1990 by [[Margaret Thatcher]]<ref name=Highbeam>{{cite web|title=Prime Minister opens technology centre; Freeze Frame January 8, 1990.(Features)|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-169006937.html|work=Birmingham Post,|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> and its success (and the income generated) allowed WMG to build two further buildings to enable expansion into other areas, including healthcare, construction, pharmaceuticals, mining, information technology and food and drink where learning from the manufacturing industry could be applied to similar processes and services.<ref name=THEJump />
This success has led several subsequent British Prime Ministers to visit WMG to demonstrate their support for WMGs innovation and applied research. [[Tony Blair]] visited WMG during the 1997 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/newsandevents/pressreleases/ne1000000081579/|title=Tony Blair visits University of Warwick|last=|first=|date=10 April 1997|website=University of Warwick|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>and 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/detail/news-photo/british-prime-minister-tony-blair-arrives-at-warwick-news-photo/830594326#british-prime-minister-tony-blair-arrives-at-warwick-university-on-picture-id830594326|title=Tony Blair Arrives at Warwick|last=|first=|date=May 10, 2001|website=Getty Images|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Election Campaigns. [[Gordon Brown]] laid the foundation stone of WMG's Digital Laboratory shortly before becoming Prime Minister <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/mediacentre/wmgnews/gordon_brown_unveils/|title=Gordon Brown unveils foundation stone of Warwick Digital Lab|last=|first=|date=20 May 2007|website=University of Warwick|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> and stated that "WMG’s work is based on very strong collaboration with industry and provides a prime example of how the knowledge created in our universities can be transferred to make a difference in the real world"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/newsandevents/pressreleases/gordon_brown_unveils/|title=Gordon Brown unveils Digital Lab foundation stone|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Warwick|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>.
[[Theresa May]] and her Chancellor [[Philip Hammond]] visited WMG together in 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/mediacentre/wmgnews/?newsItem=094d434556d003050156e63de7224e32|title=Prime Minister and Chancellor of the Exchequer visit WMG|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>. May's visit was later credited with inspiring the Prime Minister to support a British Industrial strategy by the [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|Business Secretary]], [[Greg Clark]]. Clark stated that "''Kumar'' ([[Kumar Bhattacharyya, Baron Bhattacharyya|Lord Bhattacharyya]], chairman of WMG) ''created this, all those connections, all of those links between education and jobs and technology. During all the time I’ve known Lord Bhattacharyya he’s been a big champion for the West Midlands. One of Theresa May’s first visits as Prime Minister was here and she saw for herself what is possible. As a result, I think the industrial strategy has taken such a prominent position in the post-Brexit plan''".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/government-wants-coventry-jaguar-land-12952360|title=Government wants Coventry & JLR at heart of global car industry|last=Gilbert|first=Simon|date=2017-04-28|work=coventrytelegraph|access-date=2018-03-27}}</ref>
In 2007, the group rebranded as WMG (instead of Warwick Manufacturing Group) to reflect its move to more diverse activities outside its manufacturing roots.
WMG is based in six buildings on the University of Warwick campus: * International Automotive Research Centre * International Manufacturing Centre * Engineering Management Building (Westwood campus) * International Digital Laboratory (completed 2008)<ref name=MADE>{{cite web|title=International Digital Laboratory|url=http://www.made.org.uk/images/uploads/International_digital_laboratory_new.pdf|publisher=MADE|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> * International Institute for Product and Service Innovation (completed in 2012)<ref name=IIPSI>{{cite web|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/insite/news/intnews2/iipsi/|title=International Institute for Product and Service Innovation|publisher=University of Warwick|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> * International Institute for Nanocomposites Manufacturing (completed in 2014)<ref name=IINM>{{cite web|title=International Institute for Nanocomposites Manufacturing|url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/research/multifunctional_systems/iinm|publisher=University of Warwick|accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>
The group is leading the construction of the new [[National Automotive Innovation Centre]] on the University campus.
WMG has strong links in China, where WMG has been engaged since the 1980s, and in India, where it helped establish a technical university.<ref name=THEJump />
In 2011, WMG accounted for 30 percent of the university's research activity and had over 2,500 postgraduate students, 650 studying full-time at Warwick. Just 20 of 450 staff and 10 percent of its £120 million annual research budget was funded by the [[Higher Education Funding Council for England]].<ref name=THEJump />
==Research== Research is organised into a number of research groups<ref name="WMGRes">{{
cite news |url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/research/ |publisher=WMG |title=WMG Research Areas |accessdate=2010-07-01
}}</ref> covering design, materials, manufacturing, systems and business research. Areas of focus include business innovation, low-carbon mobility and healthcare. Further programmes focus on supporting [[Small to medium enterprises|small to medium sized enterprises]] through projects such as the [[National B2B Centre|National Business to Business Centre]], the [[West Midlands Collaborative Commerce Marketplace]] and the International Institute for Product and Service Innovation.
WMG is a partner in the [[Technology Strategy Board]]'s [[High Value Manufacturing Catapult]].<ref name="WMGCatapult">{{cite news |url=https://catapult.innovateuk.org/high-value-manufacturing |publisher=Technology Strategy Board |title=High Value Manufacturing Catapult |accessdate=2012-10-11
}}</ref>
WMG is also home to the Institute of Digital Healthcare, a partnership with [[Warwick Medical School]] which aims to bring improvements to health and wellbeing through innovative digital technologies and services.
Past research programmes have included the Premium Automotive Research and Development<ref name="PARD2001">{{
cite news |url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/research/pard/ |publisher=WMG |title=Premium Automotive Research & Development |accessdate=2010-07-01
}}</ref> (PARD) Programme, the Low Carbon Vehicle Technology Project (LCVTP),<ref name="LCVTP2010">{{
cite news |url=http://www.advantagewm.co.uk/news-media-events/news/2010/new-5m-pound-lab-gives-midlands-manufacturers-super-powers.aspx |publisher=Advantage West Midlands |title=New £5m lab gives West Midlands manufacturers super powers |accessdate=2010-07-01
}}</ref><ref name="PVLT2009">{{
cite news |url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/mediacentre/wmgnews/lcvtplaunchannouncement/ |publisher=WMG |title=Launch Day For Project Set To Ensure Britain's Place At The Heart Of The Next Industrial Revolution - In Low Carbon Transportation |accessdate=2010-07-01
}}</ref> the Premium Vehicle Customer Interface Technologies (PVCIT) Centre<ref name="WMGPVCIT">{{
cite news |url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/mediacentre/wmgnews/?newsItem=094d43cd28b0d6920128b9cb011e1149 |publisher=WMG |title=Super bike helped by new £5 million lab that gives Midlands manufacturers super powers |accessdate=2011-08-08
}}</ref> and the Vehicle Energy Facility.<ref name="WMGVEF">{{
cite news |url=http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/sci/wmg/mediacentre/wmgnews/midlands_gets_a |publisher=WMG |title=Midlands gets a new unique hybrid powertrain testing facility |accessdate=2011-08-08 }}</ref>
==Education== WMG provides undergraduate engineering courses (in conjunction with the School of Engineering). However, its student population is mainly postgraduate students organised in the following way: * Full-time [[Master's degree|masters]] degrees in engineering, technology operations and business * Part-time professional programmes for those working in industry * Overseas programmes * PhD and [[Engineering Doctorate]] (EngD) programmes
WMG is a key partner in the [[WMG Academy for Young Engineers, Coventry|WMG Academy for Young Engineers]] in Coventry, a [[University Technical College]] sponsored by the University of Warwick.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Coventry Telegraph, |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/first-look-behind-scenes-coventrys-7132349|title=Watch: First look behind the scenes at Coventry’s new WMG Academy for Young Engineers |date=16 May 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>
In 2009, WMG was awarded the [[Queen's Anniversary Prize]] for Higher and Further Education,<ref name=RAT>{{cite web|title=Professor Sujit Banerji, Executive Director Postgraduate Programmes, International Manufacturing Centre The University of Warwick|url=http://www.royalanniversarytrust.org.uk/the-trust/commentary|work=The Royal Anniversary Trust - Commentary|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> formally presented at a ceremony at Buckingham Palace on 19 February 2010.<ref name=Boar>{{cite news|title=Queen’s Anniversary Prize awarded to WMG|url=http://theboar.org/2010/03/02/queens-anniversary-prize-awarded-wmg/#.UxUJm-N_srU|accessdate=3 March 2014|newspaper=The Boar|date=2 March 2010}}</ref>
